			<title>Card Hunter - A Card Based Tabletop Strategy RPG in Your Browser</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75811-Card-Hunter-A-Card-Based-Tabletop-Strategy-RPG-in-Your-Browser&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 20 Sep 2013 22:15:48 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[So, here is a game I only tried out because I've heard it mentioned in several podcasts this week and I don't have access to Hearthstone. It's pretty fun and I wasted almost all of yesterday playing it.  
 
What it is: A turn based strategy rpg that you can play for free in your browser. Instead of...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>So, here is a game I only tried out because I've heard it mentioned in several podcasts this week and I don't have access to Hearthstone. It's pretty fun and I wasted almost all of yesterday playing it. <br />
<br />
What it is: A turn based strategy rpg that you can play for free in your browser. Instead of being stat based, all the gear you equip gives you a different combination of cards to play in your deck. Each turn, you or the AI picks a card to play and that's how you perform all your actions. There are cards for attacking and moving, as well as various utility and buffs. It's a good system, although ideally I would have liked a little more planned strategy and rpg growth. It's just as luck based as you would expect in any card game where you don't draw the thing you want. I've had rounds where a character didn't get any attack cards at all.<br />
<br />
The thing I find most charming about it, and the reason why I tried it, is because of the tabletop rpg aesthetic. The playing field is a decorated mat on a table, the player characters and enemies are paper cutout figurines, etc. When you start an adventure module you open up an illustrated book detailing the story, but keep in mind the game is combat only. It isn't a fully fledged rpg.<br />
<br />
It also has multiplayer, which I wasn't going to try before the game encouraged me to do so by offering a reward if I do. It was pretty interesting. All players are more or less made equal, and the strategy at play outmatched the campaign if you like really tense matches.<br />
<br />
Having said all that, there a few things that I sense should be better, but you excuse it because it's free. Being free to play there are also microtransactions. This is completely sensible and they don't detract from the experience. You can buy new paper figurine art, you can get bonus loot in every chest, you can get bonus dungeons, etc. But everything you get for free, as far as I've played, is all you really need. The game also gives you free in game currency to get you to try the various optional features. I will say though, that if you do decide they deserve some of your money, that the prices for things are way too high. The most I would pay for something like this is $10, but $10 is the minimum buy in for currency, and the current package deal is $25.<br />
<br />
If you want more details you can read <a href="http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2013/09/17/wot-i-think-card-hunter/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">this article</a>, although do keep in mind that they way oversell the thing. It is very fun, but no where near as nuanced or amazing as the writer makes you think it is after you read that.<br />
<br />
And here's the game's website: <a href="http://www.cardhunter.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.cardhunter.com/</a></div>

]]></content:encoded>
